7371881957929569578.voice_to_text: Tripp, I wanted to honor your transparency and I wanna let you know from my perspective and my lived experience that's exactly what it looks like people too often with toxic positivity trying to tell us something that we are incapable of doing at that moment it literally took two years before that memory stopped playing like a loop in my mind it played really intensely the first few months and then it subsided then I relocated to Virginia and for an entire year every day driving to work it played in my mind it played over and over and over again and I moved to Virginia a year after Mark transition from this world and I struggled to try to find those good memories that I knew existed but they were cloaked and they were hidden by that last day that last day of Mark have going into cardiac arrest in the hotel room the emergency medical people coming in seeing myself at the end of the hallway screaming into a phone telling family and friends what was going on getting to the hospital everything about that day and climbing onto that table with his body thinking I would never see him again that entire day played over and over again I am sorry but I am glad that you're sharing and that people know that when that movie is playing over and over there's nothing wrong with us this is what grief looks like and you're sharing is helping somebody else know they're not alone so I wanted you to know you are not alone either my widow or brother we are on this together and in time there is a possibility of a changing and for me after those two years I begin to remember a lot of sweet memories a lot of wonderful memories that I had truly forgotten and didn't know they existed in the beginning so I hope the same for you I hope it doesn't last two years but whatever the time is it will be the time that your brain is ready and know I am here with you

7367126852135062826.voice_to_text: The oil and gas industry is profiting by setting off explosions in one of the world's biological hotspots. This is called seismic airgun surveying, and it's used to search the ocean for oil. A single ship can blast every 10 seconds, 24 hours a day, seven days a week, for months on end. The air guns are like mini cannons and the blast can exceed 235 decibels, which is hundreds of times more intense than a jet engine. A marine mammal in the vicinity would be deafened. Most of this is happening in the Gulf of Mexico, home to some of the world's most endangered species. The blasts can inflict permanent, even fatal, hearing damage on whales, dolphins, even affect the plankton that's the foundation of the ocean food web. The sound waves can be heard across the entire Gulf. This near constant level of noise can mask vital calls that marine mammals depend on to survive. The Biden administration has a chance to reign in this harmful activity. Unfortunately, it issued a new rule that would still allow extensive seismic testing in the Gulf of Mexico. The environmental law organization Earthjustice is asking the administration to change course and correct the rule, so that it protects Gulf wildlife from seismic air gun surveys. 7364092507170295086.voice_to_text: Me. Something a job has taught you that you will never, ever forget, no matter what. That they don't care. They don't care that you got in a wreck on the way to work. They don't care that your babysitter didn't show up. They don't care that you just bought a house. This is coming from someone who sat on the executive board, with the CEO, with the C O O, with all of the higher UPS. They don't care. They don't care what you have going outside of work. It is about the result. It is about the deliverable. And the sooner you remove the emotion out of the work that you do, the further that you can go. Because when you start to think that they care if you had a bad day, then you give yourself an excuse to have a bad day. When you think that they hear that you're doing really well in your personal life, you give yourself an excuse. When you remove the emotion, you will go further. Show up, be passionate about the work that you were doing. If you are. If you don't care about the work you're doing, do the bare minimum, but take the emotion out of it. And stop people thinking that people care. It wasn't until I understood this that I doubled my salary and was able to get promoted. It sounds cold, but it's true.

7362324510042885418.video_description: Animated movies and shows keep getting mediocre live action adaptations. same universe, different story is *chefs kiss* #animation #movies #avatarthelastairbender
7362324510042885418.voice_to_text: Are live action adaptations of shows ever a good thing? Take a look at all these live action movies slash shows adapted from animation. How many of them make you say I would rather watch the live action adaptation than the animated original? For me, Scooby Doo movies, maybe Ruroni Kenshin, and that's it. I don't give a crap about the rest. Compared to their animated counterparts, some of these are downright bad. And the good ones usually aren't better than the original animated show or movie. So why even bother with live action in the first place? Stupid reasons. For starters. 1. People like making money. We already know that most of Hollywood would rather produce a spin on an already beloved IP than create anything truly new. The latter is too much of a risk. God forbid you take risks in art. Art is about profit for shareholders. Second, I think some people view animation as a lesser medium for kids or adults that never grew out of their childlike interest, and that turning animation into live action can make it blockbuster worthy. Also, while I don't think that live action adaptations are made with Oscars in mind, I think it's interesting that over the span of 96 years, only three animated films have been nominated for Best Picture. Animation isn't always given the same respect that live action is. I can, however, think of two good reasons to adapt animation into live action. First, to open up The story to a wider audience, kind of catering to people that have the perspective I just mentioned. As much as I love animation, I know there's people that don't care to watch animated shows, but would probably love the story if it was presented to them in live action. Honestly though, I'm in favor of just encouraging more people to watch animated shows and movies. Second to tell a brand new story that takes place in the animated original universe. An example of this would be Scooby Doo. One of the potential reasons that the Scooby Doo movies were enjoyable is because they were written for live action. They didn't try to one to one recreate the most popular episodes of the animated show. However, I think there's some aspects of animated shows that are really hard to adapt to live action, like certain visual goofs, character designs, and the overall vibe, for lack of better words. Like a live action Adventure Time, no matter how good their CGI budget is, probably won't feel like Adventure Time. I think it's important when adapting from animation to live action to consider the differences and strengths of each medium and really think how could this story or these characters benefit from or be expanded upon in a live action setting? Because a one to one recreation of animation more often than not falls flat.

7358585631947214123.video_description: The best culinary experience I’ve ever had— dining at Iris in Rosendal, Norway inside of the Salmon Eye. A 6 hour long, 18 course “expedition dining” experience, it’s not for the faint of heart— but if you’re someone who loves food and adventure, this is something you need to add to your bucket list! #irisrestaurant #salmoneye #expeditiondining #themenu #fyp
7358585631947214123.voice_to_text: Have you heard of expedition dining? This is Restaurant Iris, located inside of a floating art installation called The Salmon Eye, nestled within the breathtaking Norwegian fjords. To get there, you take an electric boat with fellow Extreme Foodies, which first stops at the Chef's Boathouse, where you served a couple of amazing bites and a glass of local cider. Then after another short ride, it's time for the main event, dining inside of the Salmon Eye. The entire experience is a journey beginning under the water surface, literally complete with a thematic seaweed crisp that you collect yourself, and a dreamy sea urchin moose, their version of chips and dip, to welcome you into their space. You then move upstairs and into the lounge for a few more incredible bites. Next, more amazing dishes take center stage at a table with breathtaking views. Each dish had a story inspired by the surrounding nature, from the mountains to the ocean, and all the ingredients are sourced as locally as possible. Then it's time to wind down back in the lounge with tea, coffee and chocolates before heading back to reality. Goodbye, Iris. Until next time.

Welcome to the Fantasy Annexe. There's an argument to be made that no one fully understood how crucial it was to destroy the ring. But I think that's debatable. There are more impactful reasons for Elrond's actions. For one, by the time Sauron is defeated, the elves and humans had been fighting in the War of the Last Alliance against him for over 10 years. I think it's very fair to assume that Elrond and Isildur are close by the end of this war. On top of that, Isildur is Elrond's nephew, a few generations removed. You gonna ask him to take out a family member like that? If you're ignoring their relationship, consider the politics. Elrond and Isildur are the highest ranking members of the elven and human armies, respectively. If word got out that Elrond killed Isildur, the political ramifications would be devastating. It may have even started a second war, this time between elves and humans. If none of those reasons are good enough, then I ask you this. At the end of Return of the King, Frodo and Sam find themselves in a similar situation when Frodo refuses to destroy the ring. Do we legitimately think Sam would have or should have pushed Frodo into Mount Doom? Just because we didn't see Elrond and Isildur’s story and struggle doesn't mean that we can expect Elrond to have done any different than Sam. Follow for more fantasy content.
